column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HRS. ON 11-01-94, A CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT (CWM) DRIVER (GARY BRIAN VEACH), WAS LOADING A SINGLE DRUM FROM THE FRITO-LAY FACILITY LOCATED AT 1450 WEST MARICOPA HWY., IN CASA GRANDE, ARIZONA. DURING THE TRANSFER OF THE DRUM OFF A PALLET ONTO THE FLAT-BED TRAILER, THE 55 GALLON POLY DRUM FAILED, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF THE FOLLOWING MATERIAL.  RQ WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S., 8, UN1760, 11 (D002, D002), ACETIC ACID.  THE WASTE WAS TO BE TRANSPORTED TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC.- PHOENIX SERVICE CENTER.  THIS LOCATED 2301 WEST BROADWAY ROAD IN PHOENIX, ARIZONA.  THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM, SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR-BOARD OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO BOTH CONCRETE AND DIRT GROUND. SOME OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE DRIVER. HIS CLOTHING WAS QUICKLY REMOVED, HE SHOWERED AND WAS GIVEN CLEAN CLOTHING.  ON 11-01-94, CWM (GOLDEN), CONTACTED MR. DAN LARSON AT THE ARIZONA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY TO REPORT THE SPILL AND POTENTIAL RQ RELEASE OF DO22 CHLOROFORM.  THE REPORT NUMBER IS 94-063-F.  THE APPARENT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DEFECTIVE/FAILEED 55-GALLON POLY DRUM.  FRITO-LAY PERSONNEL, MANAGED TO CONTROL THE AREA OF THE RELEASE.  CWM PERSONNEL ON 11-02-94, REMEDIATED THE SOILS, CONCRETE, TRAILER AND ANCILLARY EQUIPMENT. THE DRUM WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE AND IT'S CONTENTS WERE OVERPACKED.  ALL MATERIAL WERE MANIFESTED TO CWM-PHOENIX.  THE DRIVER FOR CWM WAS SENT FOR A MEDICAL EXAMINATION ON 11-01-94 AT MBI.  A DOCTORS RELEASE WAS OBTAINED.

WHEN DRUM WAS BEING UNLOAD WITH A BROKEN ATTACHMENT A PALLET THAT LOADED (BOWLED STACKED) FELL SHIFT THE DRUM PUNCTURING THE SIDE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUM ROMEO PENA NOTICED THAT THE DRUM WAS LEAKING AND TOLD ME ABOUT THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS ABOUT 5 TO 6 OUNCES THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS WITH THE DOCK MAKING COPY.

OUR TRUCK WAS PUMPING MATERIAL INTO CUSTOMER TANK.  CUSTOMER HAD A NEW EMPLOYEE RECEIVING THE MATERIAL.  THE NEW EMPLOYEE WAS TO SIGNAL OUR DRIVER TO TURN OFF HIS PUMP WHEN THE PRODUCT REACHED A CERTAIN LEVEL IN CUSTOMERS TANK.  THE NEW EMPLOYEE MIS-JUDGED HOW FAST THE PRODUCT LEVEL WAS RISING, AND SIGNALED OUR DRIVER TO TURN HIS PUMP OFF AS THE TANK WAS REACHING THE POINT OF OVERFLOW, BY THE TIME THE FLOW WAS STOPPED THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS SPILLED.  THE PRODUCT WAS TOTALLY CONTAINED ON CONCRETE WITH DIKE WALLS AND CLEANED UP USING APPROPRIATE MEASURES.

DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED DRIED SPILL WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER.  IT APPEARS THE PUNCTURE TO THE SHIPMENT MAY HAVE OCCURED BY PUSHING FREIGHT FORWARD DURING LOADING OF TRAILER.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED, THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED AND CLEAN UP PERFORMED PER HAZMAT INSTRUCTIONS.  THE DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: ON SATURDAY, 11/12/94 AT 14:00, DELTA DISTRIBUTORS, INCORPORATED OF ST. GABRIEL, LOUISIANA, DELIVERED A LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO A CUSTOMER, INTERNATIONAL PAPER IN PINEVILLE, LOUISIANA.  THE DELTA DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO UNLOAD UPON ARRIVAL AT THE PLANT.  THE DRIVER UNLOADED FOR ABOUT 10 MINUTES AND NOTICED ACID COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TANK.  THE DIRVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED UNLOADING AND NOTIFIED INTERNATIONAL PAPER EMPLOYEES.  INTERNATIONAL PROCEEDED WITH CLEAN UP AND REPORTING. INTERNATIONAL PAPER MISGUAGED THEIR HUDROCHLORIC STORAGE TANK.  ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF ACID SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE DYKE CONTAINMENT WALL.

DOCKMAN WAS BACKING OUT OF TRAILER WITH TOTE TANK ON FORKS.  FORKLIFT GOT HUNG ON DOCKBOARD, WHICH WAS SLIGHTLY ELEVATED INTO TRAILER.  THE JOLT FROM THE IMPACT, THE RELEASE OF THE FORKLIFT FROM THE DOCKBOARD DOWN THE INCLINE, COMBINED WITH THE CENTRIFUGAL FORCE CREATED BY TURNING DOWN THE INCLINE, DUMPED THE TOTE TANK OFF THE FORKS, POPPING THE LID OFF, AND SPILLING 60-70% OF THE CONTENTS.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH DRY ABSORBANT AND SAND.  THE ABSORBANT AND SAND WAS THEN SHOVELED INTO 55- GALLON CONTAINERS.  THE CONTAINERS WERE THEN TURNED OVER TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY GROUP (ATLANTIC BEACH, FL) FOR PROPER PACKAGING, TRANSPORTING AND DISPOSAL.  THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT LEFT IN THE TOTE TANK WAS RETURNED BACK TO THE SHIPPER VIA AAA COOPER TRANSPORTATION.

ON NOVEMBER 6,1994 BETWEEN 10:30 AND 11:00 OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT TRUCKSTOPS OF AMERICA.  AT THIS PARTICULAR TRUCK STOP, THERE IS ONE DROP DESIGNATED FOR TAKING STICK READINGS AND THE OTHER DROP IS DESIGNATED FOR DROPPING FUEL PER TANK.  OUR DRIVER MISTAKENLY LEFT THE CAP OFF OF THE LOCATION WERE HE GOT HIS STICK READINGS AND PROCEEDED TO DROP PRODUCT. WHEN THE TANK BECAME CLOSE TO BEING FULL, THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO ESCAPE FROM THE LOCATION USED FOR STICK READINGS.  THESE TWO SEPARATE LOCATIONS AREA 30 FEET APART SO OUR DRIVER FAILED TO IMMEDIATELY NOTICE THE FUEL SPILLING.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND ASSISTED WITH THE CLEANUP.  THERE WAS NO PERMANENT DAMAGE.

THEY DID NOT DETECT ANY LIQUID LEAK BUT BELIEVED THEY COULD SEE SOME VAPORS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THEY TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP ABOUT 0.5 TURN.  NO LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED.

THE DRIVER'S EYES AND THROAT BEGAN TO BURN, AND HE WAS LATER TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL, WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, WERE CALLED, AND THEY TOOK OVER CLEAN UP AND SECUREMENT OF PLASTIC DRUMS.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALSO CALLED TO THE SCENE.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO MONSANTO CHEMICAL COMPANY LOCATED AT 730 WORCESTER STREET IN SPRINGFIELD, MA, IN ORDER TO PICK UP A LOAD OF WASTE RESIN SOLUTION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR BEGAN TO LOAD THE PRODUCT INTO THE TANK FROM 55-GALLON DRUMS USED TO STORE THE MATERIAL.  THIS TASK WAS ACCOMPLISHED USING A DRUM WAND ATTACHED TO THE VACUUM HOSE OF THE TANK.  DURING THIS OPERATION, THE FITTING CONNECTING THE DRUM WAND TO THE TRANSFER HOSE FAILED, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO SPRAY ONTO THE UNIFORM OF THE DRIVER CONDUCTING THE TRANSFER OPERATION.  THE LOADING OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN, AND THE DRIVER WENT TO AN EMERGENCY SHOWER, WHERE HE RINSED THE PRODUCT FROM HIS UNIFORM.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE RELEASE WAS LOCALIZED TO THE UNIFORM OF THE DRIVER, THERE WAS NO SPILL DEBRIS ASSOCIATED WITH THE RELEASE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE DRUM WAND, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE THREADS AT THE CONNECTION TO THE TRANSFER HOSE HAD CORRODED, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  PRIOR TO RESUMING THE OPERATION, A NEW FITTING WAS ATTACHED, AND THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL ANCILLARY EQUIPMENT AS PART OF HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION TO INSURE THAT ALL ITEMS ARE IN WORKING ORDER AND TO OBTAIN REPLACEMENT EQUIPMENT IF DEFECTS ARE IDENTIFIED.
WHILE FILLING ONE TANK AND THINKING THE TANKS WERE CONNECTED WITH OVERFLOW PROTECTION, THE TANK OVERFILLED AND CAME BACK OUT FITTING.

column168: WASTE MINERAL SPIRITS WAS BEING TRANSFERRED INTO THE TANKER.  THE OPERATOR UNDERESTIMATED THE VOLUME BEING PUMPED.  ABOUT 50 GALLONS OVERFLOWED THE TOP MANHOLE.  ALL OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAD (COATED, SLOPED, CONCRETE PAD).   THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PUMPED FROM THE SUMP INTO DRUMS.  THE CONTAINMENT SPILL RESIDUE WAS ALSO RECOVERED WITH CORN COB AND SORBANT PADS.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ENSCO, INC. LOCATED AT AMERICAN OIL ROAD IN EL DORADO, AR TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND'S SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 INDEPENDENCE ROAD IN CLEVELAND, OH THE CONTAINERS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER VAN TRAILER USING A BARREL GRABBER THAT ATTACHES TO THE TOP LIP OF THE CONTAINERS CRACKED CAUSING THE DRUM TO FALL FROM THE BARREL GRABBER WHICH RESULTED IN A 12 INCH LONG CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ESCAPED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND THE HARD PACKED SOIL PARKING AREA. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. APPROXIMATELY 6 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS GENERATED AND DISPOSED OF AT A FULLY LICENCED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL EQUIPMENT OPERATORS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO THE SAFE OPERATING PRACTICES OF FORK-LIFTS AND ATTACHMENTS USED TO MOVE CONTAINERS.

A TANK TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO DRAGON CEMENT LOCATED AT ROUTE #1 IN THOMASTON, ME FROM CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 37 RUMMERY ROAD IN SOUTH PORTLAND, ME IN ORDER TO DELIVER A LOAD OF SPECIFICATION USED FUEL OIL. UPON ARRIVAL AT DRAGON CEMENT, THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO THE RECEIVING TANK. DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 GALLONS OF FUEL HAD ESCAPED FROM A VALVE ON THE VEHICLE THAT WAS NOT BEING USED IN THE TRANSFER OPERATION. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY HALTED THE PRODUCT TRANSFER, PLACED A CONTAINMENT PAIL UNDER THE LEAKING VALVE AND NOTIFIED HIS HOME DISPATCHER. A FIELD SERVICE CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW INSPECTED THE TANK AND DISCOVERED THAT THE VALVE HAD BECOME LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. THE CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND CONTAINERIZED ALL SPILL DEBRIS. THIS MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO A PROPERLY LICENCED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. ONCE THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP, THE DRIVER TIGHTENED THE LOOSE VALVE AND RESUMED THE OFF-LOADING PROCEDURE. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL EQUIPMENT, VALVES AND FITTINGS AS PART OF HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION TO INSURE THAT ALL ITEMS ARE IN WORKING ORDER AND TO OBTAIN REPLACEMENT EQUIPMENT IF DEFECTS ARE IDENTIFIED. IN ADDITION, THE DRIVER IS TO INSURE THAT ALL VALVES ARE TIGHT AND IN THE CLOSED POSITION WHEN NOT IN USE.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGED WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE ARRIVED BY TRUCK FROM OUR BIRMINGHAM RAMP OPERATION AFTER BEING FLOWN INTO BHM FROM MEMPHIS, TENN. THE SHIPMENT ORIGINATED IN BALTIMORE, MD AND WAS FLOWN FROM BALTIMORE INTO MEMPHIS, TENN FOR SORTING TO FINAL DESTINATION. THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN OFF THE INBOUND TRUCK INTO GADSEN, AL AND THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED ALMOST IMMEDIATELY. APPARENTLY THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DAMAGED ALONG THE WAY CAUSING SPILLAGE FROM THE INNER CONTAINERS. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND OPENED TO REVEAL SEVERAL CONTAINERS ON THE INSIDE OF THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX. THERE WERE THREE GLASS MASON JARS ON THE INSIDE OF THE BOX AND ONE OF THE JARS WAS BROKEN. ON THE BROKEN JAR WAS A LABEL THAT THAD IDENTIFIED THE COMMODITY AS CARBON TETRACHLORIDE, A DIVISION 6.1 (POISON) THERE WERE "NO" HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THIS PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED. THE F.A.A. WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING SHUTTLED TO THE EWR SORTING FACILITY FOR OUTBOUND TRANSPORT WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURED. THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED AT THE EWR FACILITY AND APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING. THE COMMODITY WAS GIVEN BACK TO THE SHUTTLE DRIVER AND BROUGHT BACK TO OUT STRATFORD FACILITY. THE COMMODITY WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND RELOAD AND SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL THAT THE CAP/LID ON THE JERRICAN WAS NOT SEALING PROPERLY.  THIS ALLOWED THE SUBSTANCE TO SEEP OUT OF THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER CAUSING LEAKAGE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

A RANDOLPH'S INC. TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DENATURED ALCOHOL INTO MOLO OIL COMPANY'S ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE THOUGHT THE LOAD WOULD FIT INTO THE TANK SO PROCEEDED, UNTIL FINISHED.  THE TANK RAN OVER AND THE SPILL WASN'T DETECTED TILL LATER BECAUSE IT HAD SETTLED BELOW THE GRAVEL, WHICH SURFACED THE DIKED, CONTAINMENT AREA.  AT THAT TIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, DNR, AND HAZMAT CLEAN-UP COMPANY WERE NOTIFIED TO COME IN AND CONTROL THE SITUATION.   THIS PARTICULAR DRIVER, HAS BEEN IN OUR EMPLOY FOR LESS THAN 60 DAYS AND WILL HAVE TO UNDER TAKE MORE INTENSIVE TRAINING IN THE FIELDS OF HAZMAT REGULATIONS AND COMPANY POLICIES INVOLVING UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  ALSO, ALL OTHER EMPLOYEES WILL BE MADE AWARE OF THE INCIDENT AND THE POSSIBILITY OF DISQUALIFICATION FOR SUCH NEGLIENCE.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR-SEMI CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS PUMPING JET A FROM AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK INTO THE COMPARTMENT OF THE CARGO TANK TRAILER. AT THE COMPLETION OF FILLING THE COMPARTMENT THE DRIVER DISCONNECTION THE LOADING HOSE FROM THE CONNECTION TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE LIFTED THE HOSE UP IN ORDER FOR THE PUMP TO COMPLETE SUCTION OF THE REMAINING FUEL IN THE HOSE INTO THE CARGO TANK TRAILER COMPARTMENT.  THERE WAS A MIXTURE OF AIR AND FUEL IN THE HOSE.  AS THE PUMP SUCKED THE AIR IT CAUSED A SUDDEN SURGE UP INTO THE CARGO TANK COMPARTMENT CAUSING THE FUEL IN THE COMPARTMENT TO BACK PRESSURE INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY TUBE.  THIS SURGE CAUSED THE FUEL IN THE COMPARTMENT TO BACK PRESSURE INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY TUBE.  THIS SURGE CAUSED THE FUEL TO FLOW ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON PAVEMENT.  IT DID NOT FLOW ONTO GROUND OR INTO ANY STORM OR SEWER DRAINS.  THE ALLIED SIGNAL FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED AND CONTAINED THE AREA.  CLEAN UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY THE USE OF ABSORBENT.  A STRIP OF CEMENT WAS REMOVED ALONG THE SEAM LINE TO ASSURE THAT THER WAS NO GROUND COMBINATION.

RECOMMENDED ACTION TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS: WHEN THERE IS DOUBT AS TO THE ABILITY FOR THE STORAGE TANK TO HOLD ALL OF THE SUPPLIED MATERIAL, THE CUSTOMER SHOULD MEASURE THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE CARGO TANK TO ENSURE ENOUGH CAPACITY IN THEIR STORAGE TANK TO HOLD ALL PRODUCT.

A VAN TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO PRESTOLITE ELECTRIC, INC., LOCATED AT 400 WEST MAIN STREET IN ARCADE, NY, TO PICK UP A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE DESTINED FOR SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC, LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE LOADING AREA WHERE HE BEGAN TO LOAD THE DRUMS WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF EMPLOYEES FROM PRESTOLITE ELECTRIC.  DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT ONE DRUM CONTAINING TRICHLOROETHYLENE HAD DEVELOPED A MINOR LEAK ALONG THE SIDE SEAM AND REQUESTED THAT IT BE REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE IN ORDER TO PLACE IT IN A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  UPON MOVING THE DRUM, LEAK AT THE SEAM EXPANDED, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND A FULLY CONTAINED LOADING AREA.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDIDRY, AND RECONTAINERIZED THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE DAMAGED CONTAINER.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO PROPER STORAGE CONTAINERS PENDING DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS SENT TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR AN OUT PATIENT EVALUATION AS A PRECAUTION BECAUSE HE WAS EXPOSED TO THE TRICHLOROETHYLENE THAT WAS RELEASED.  THE RESULTS OF THE EVALUATION WERE NEGATIVE, AND THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED BACK TO ACTIVE DUTY THE SAME DAY.  ALSO NOTE THAT THE DRIVER WAS NOT ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

UNLOADING PROCESS WAS IMMEDIATELY HALTED, AIR PRESSURE WAS RELEASED A DIAPHRAM TYPE SUCTION PUMP WAS HOOKED TO UNLOADING LINES, AND AN ADDITIONAL CARTON BASIN WAS PUT UNDER LEAKING AREA. MANLEY-REGAN CHEMICALS HAS HAD THE TRAILER PROFESSIONALLY INSPECTED SINCE THE INCIDENT AND HAS NOTED THAT THE INNER LINER FAILED, CAUSING SUBSEQUENT FAILURE OF THE TANK SHELL.  A COMPLETE RE-INSPECTION OF MANLEY-REGAN CHEMICALS' FLEET WAS PERFORMED WITH NO FAULTS NOTED.

ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PLACED AROUND BAG AND NO FURTHER SEEPAGE WAS OBSERVED. LOAD WAS TAKEN ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM. IT IS VERY POSSIBLE THIS WAS ONLY WATER.

THE SPILL AREA WAS CONTAINED TO THE CEMENT DRIVE WAY OF THE SERVICE STATION.  IT DID NOT FLOW TO GROUND AREA OR TO ANY SEWER OR STORM DRAIN. WHEN THE TRUCK ARRIVED AT FISHER SCIENTIFIC, ITASCA, IL, A SLIGHT ODOR WAS DETECTED BY THE RECEIVER WHO REFUSED TO UNLOAD AND PERFORM A SEARCH AND DISCOVERY.  NO MATERIAL WAS FOUND ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND NONE HAD ESCAPED FROM CONTAINERS THAT COULD BE SEEN.  THE SHIPPING PAPERS WERE NOT SIGNED REFUSED, BUT THE LOAD WAS REMOVED FROM FISHER'S PROPERTY PER THEIR ORDER.  AT TRL'S DROP YARD IN CHICAGO, MTI PERSONNEL WERE HIRED TO DO A SEARCH AND DISCOVERY (SEE ATTACHED).  A SLIGHT ODOR WAS DETECTED, BUT NO LEAK WAS FOUND.  AGAIN THE LOAD WAS REFUSED AT FISHER SCIENTIFIC, BUT NOT STATED SO ON THE BILLS OF LADING.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN ORDED BACK TO FISHER SCIENTIFIC IN SOMERVILLE, NJ BY TRL BECAUSE OF LACK OF COOPERATION. THE TRUCK MADE A ROUTINE STOP OFF AT TRL'S PITTSTON, PA FACILITY FOR FUEL AND MAINTENANCE.  THIS WRITER TOOK ADVANTAGE OF THIS S/O TO PERFORM A SEARCH AND DISCOVERY.  THE ODOR WAS NOT PRESENT AT THIS TIME, BUT A STAIN WAS FOUND ONE QUARTER OF THE WAY INTO THE TRAILER ON A PALLET THAT WAS PILED WITH FIVE GALLON PAILS.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT TWO OF THE 64 CANS LOADED HAD BEEN PUSHED TOGETHER BY A FORKLIFT CAUSING THEM TO BUMP AGAINST THE OTHER FREIGHT THAT WAS ALSO PILED UPON PALLETS.  THESE OTHER PALLETS CAUSED THE CANS TO DENT AND SPLIT WHEN PUSHED FORWARD DURING THE LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCESS.  SEE PICTURES. BECAUSE OF THE RAPID EVAPORATION, THE ODOR WOULD VARY AT SEVERAL INTENSITIES FROM NONE TO VERY APPARENT.  THE CANS WERE ESTIMATED TO HAVE LOST ONE QUART EACH.  THEY WERE THEN PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND SHIPPED BACK TO FISHER SCIENTIFIC IN SOMERVILLE, NJ, WHERE THEY WERE AGAIN REFUSED ALTHOUGH THE PRODUCT WAS FISHER'S.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH HAZMAT EMERGENCY SERVICES OF PARSIPPANY, NJ TO COLLECT AND DISPOSE THE MATERIALS IN A PROPER MANNER. THEY (HMES) WERE CONTRACTED BY FISHER SCIENTIFIC. CYCLE CHEM OF ELIZABETH, NJ PERFORMED THE ACTUAL DISPOSAL. (SEE ATTACHED)

THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

RADIOACTIVE SHIPMENT WAS BLOWN OF CONVEYOR BELT TRUCK BY A STRONG GUST OF WIND SHIPMENT WAS RUN OVER BY CB TRUCK AS IT WAS BACKING AWAY FROM AIRCRAFT (APPROX. 20 FEET FROM AIRCRAFT) DRIVER OF CONVEYOR WAS NOT AWARE SHIPMENT HAD BLOWN OFF-WHEN. DISCOVERED LEAD RSS CLEARED AREA OF PERSONNEL CONTACTED ACTING RSS JEFFERIES TO SCENE AND RECOVERED SHIPMENT-SHIPMENT WAS THEN ISOLATED TO AREA BY BOARDING GATE F64-NOTIFICATION LISTED IN ORDER: USAIR STATION MGR, CHICAGO FIRE DEPT., SYSTEM CONTROL CENTER, REGIONAL OFFICE DEPT OF ENERGY, SHIPPER, GROUND SERVICES DUTY MANAGER, FAA CIVIL AVIATION SECURITY OFFICE MGR GRD OPS ILL DEPT OF NUCLEAR SAFETY CONTACTED RSS JEFFERIES FOR DETAILS SHIPMENT WAS DECLARED NOT TO BE EMITTING RADIATION AND WAS SAFE. SHIPMENT WAS ENCASED IN METAL CAN WITH PLASTIC BAG AND SAND THE SEALED.

AGENT WAS LOADING AIRFREIGHT SHIPMENT INTO REAR BIN OF FLIGHT 415 TO SAN FRANCISCO. AS AGENT WAS PLACING CARGO ON THE FLOOR OF THE REAR BIN HE NOTICED SOME LIQUID DRIPPING FROM ONE OF THE BOXES. THE BOXES WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND A HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED. THE BOXES CONTAINED DRY ICE AND THE SHIPMENT WAS IN TRANSIT FOR 3 DAYS. THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS IN TOUCH WITH THE CONSIGNEE AND THE SHIPMENT WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY THE HAZMAT TEAM. THE REAR CARGO BIN WAS CLEANED WITH A WATER/BLEACH SOLUTION AND THE AIRCRAFT WAS PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE.
CUSTOMER ADVISED DRIVER THAT TANK WOULD HOLD PRODUCT. DURING UNLOADING PROCESS, THE TANK FILLED AND OVER-FLOWED. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS WAS SPILLED AND CONTAINED ON THE PAVEMENT.

DRIVER WAS RETURNING TO HIS TERMINAL AFTER OFF-LOADING. DRIVER HAD PUMPED OFF RPODUCT AND WAS UNABLE TO BLOW ALL PRODUCT FROM THE DISCHARGE HOSE. IN ORDER TO AVOID A SPILL, THE DRIVER HAD PLUGGED THE HOSE ENDS. ONE OF THE PLUGS VIBRATED LOOSE AND THE PRODUCT SPILLED INTO THE HOSE TROUGH. AS VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING, THE PRODUCT BLEW OUT OF THE TROUGHT IN A SPRAY FASHION.

AT APPROX 1012 A. WHITE AT C.P. INDUSTRIES OFF LOADING, THE FORK TRUCK OPERATOR STRUCK A FORK THRU A DRUM OF TRIETHANE 1-1-1, I RUSHED TO TURN DRUM UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT LOSS OF FLUID. PLACED DRUM ON PALLET TO HAVE IT REMOVED FROM MY TRUCK. CPI PROVIDED MSDS BUT HAD NO CLEAN UP MATERIALS. CALLED BOB CAIN APPROX 1015 AM TO ADVISE HIM OF THE SITUATION. HE DIRECTED CLINT BERLIN TO COME TO CPI WITH ABSORBANT AND OVERPACK WE PUT DAMAGED DRUM INTO OVERPAK. CLINT THEN TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO DYCE IN OGDEN.  I DEPARTED APPROX 1200 TO CONTINUE BY DELIVERIES.

OUR DRIVER HAD STARTED TO DELIVER HIS CARGO AT DESTINATION WHEN THE CUSTOMER TOLD HIM TO STOP SINCE THE PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE OFF COLOR. THE CUSTOMER THEN DECIDED TO REJECT THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT AND OUR DRIVER STARTED TO DISCONNECT THE AIR LINE TO PREPARE TO DEPART. AS HE ATTEMPTED TO DISCONNECT THE PVC AIR LINE ON THE TRAILER CRACKED AND MIST BLEW FROM THE CRACK UNTIL THE PRESSURE BLED OFF THE TRAILER. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS STOPPED AT THE TOLL PLAZA AT THE PEACE BRIDGE DUE TO ODOR ORIGINATING FROM HIS TRAILER. OUR PERSONNEL WERE ADVISED AND THE AUTHORITIES SHUT DOWN THE BRIDGE. THE BUFFALO POLICE AND FIREMEN RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. WE DISPATCHED EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO THE SCENE AND THEY WERE ADVISED BY THE FIRE CHIEF AT THE SCENE THAT THEY COULD NOT FINE ANY LEAKAGE BUT THAT THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR. OUR PERSONNEL WERE ALLOWED TO INSPECT THE TRAILER AND FOUND THAT THE ODOR WAS STRONGEST IN THE CRASH BOX, DOME AREA. THEY SUSPECTED A PROBLEM WITH EITHER THE VACUUM BREAKER OR FUSIBLE CAP LOCATED IN THE AREA. BOTH ITEMS WERE REPLACED AND OUR DRIVER WAS ASKED TO MOVE HIS UNIT BACK AND FORTH TO CHECK FOR ANY OTHER PROBLEMS. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A POSSIBLE PROBLEM WITH TWO CLEAN OUT CAPS AND THE GASKETS WERE ALSO REPLACED. THE UNIT WAS AGAIN MOVED BACK AND FORTH AND AT THIS POINT IT APPEARED THAT THE PROBLEM HAD BEEN CORRECTED. THE AUTHORITIES THEN ESCORTED OUR VEHICLE TO OUR TERMINAL IN TONAWANDA, NY.

THE YARD AND TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP AND THE WASTE WAS PLACED INTO NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS ALSO PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH APPROPRIATE LABELS AND MARKINGS.  THE WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY THE RESPONSE TEAM AT A CERTIFIED LANDFILL.  THE STEEL DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

THE GTW EXTRA 530.1 EAST, TRAIN 142, WAS ENROUTE WITH 141 CARS IN CONSIST. AT A PASSING POINT, A WESTBOUND TRAIN INFORMED TRAIN 142 OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE SLIGHT TRICKLING OF GRAYISH-WHITE SMOKE COMING FROM A TRAILER ON FLAT CAR CN 263367, WHICH WAS THE 41ST CAR FROM HEAD END OF TRAIN. TRAIN 142 ADVANCED TO THE FIRST AVAILABLE SET POINT WITH INTENTIONS OF LEAVING THE CAR; HOWEVER, THE TRACK WAS OCCUPIED BY MAINTENANCE OF WAY EQUIPMENT. TRAIN DISPATCHER WAS ADVISED AND INFORMED TRAIN 142 TO SET CAR OUT AT MORRICE. ARRANGEMENTS WOULD BE MADE TO HAVE FIRE DEPARTMENT AT THE SITE. ON ARRIVAL AT MORRICE, FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS PRESENTED WITH THE SHIPPING PAPERS AND A VISUAL INSPECTION OF TRAILER CSXZ 239782 WAS PERFOMED. DUE TO HIGH TEMPERATURE OF HEAT RADIATING FROM TRAILER, A DETERMINATION WAS MADE FOR SAFETY REASONS TO LEAVE CN263367 AT LOCATION ON EASTWARD MAIN LTRACK. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED FROM TRAIN. THIS INCIDENT WAS FURTHER COMPOUNDED BY THE SEVERAL QUESTIONS RAISED, PLUS CONSIDERABLE TIME WASTE IN OBTAINING EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION. AT 1240 HOURS HEAT AND SMOKE CONFINED WITHIN THE TRAILER CAUSED THE ROOF TO DISLODGE, EMITTING HEAVY BLACK SMOKE. BETWEEN 20 TO 25 HOMES IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA WERE EVACUATED AND AS A CAUTIONARY MEASURE, TWO SCHOOLS BORDERING THE TWO-MILE DOWNWIND PERIMETER WERE DISMISSED EARLY. FIRE WAS SAFETY AND SUCCESSFULLY EXTINGUISHED AT 2015 HOURS.

REEDER ARRIVED AND DID NOT OBSERVE ANY RESIDUAL LIQUID ON THE CAR. SEAL C.R.A.M. WAS REMOVED FROM THE COVER/HANDLE OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HOUSING. THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS HAND TIGHT AND A LIQUID RESIDUE WAS VISIBLE AROUND THE SHAFT. REEDER TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT. THE CAR WAS THEN RESEALED WITH UPRR 483356. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC REPORT #32205. BARRY CUNNINGHAM WAS CONTACTED AT COASTAL REFINING.

ON NOVEMBER 02, 1994 AT APPROXIMATELY 1245 HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEAN WOMACK WAS CONTACTED BY MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS LARRY ERWIN. MR. ERWIN INFORMED S/A WOMACK THAT MR. MICKEY PARKER, SUPERINTENDENT OF OLIN CHEMICAL, SHREVEPORT, LA., INFORMED HIM THAT LAST EVENING AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS THE CREW ON TRAIN LRE66-01 CAUSED A CHEMICAL SPILL. MR ERWIN STATED THAT THE TRAIN CREW FAILED TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT TO HIM. S/A WOMACK CONTACTED MR. MICKEY PARKER, SUPERINTENDENT OF OLIN CHEMICAL, SHREVEPORT, LA. MR PARKER STATED THAT THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THE TRAIN CREW MADE A JOINT WITH GATX 15377, WHICH HAD UNLOADING HOSE CONNECTED. MR. PARKER STATED THAT THE HOSE CAME LOOSE, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID (SPENT) ON THE GROUND. MR. PARKER FURTHER STATED THAT HIS EMPLOYEES NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLAGE SHORTLY AFTER IT OCCURRED. S/A WOMACK CONTACTED STATE POLICE AND INFORMED THEM OF THIS INCIDENT (94-4577). S/A WOMACK ALSO REPORTED INCIDENT TO D.E.Q. AGENT BURNS DOSS.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPONDE TO A LEAKING PACKAGE ON SORT AISLE 1. I FOUND THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SO I SECURED THE AREA AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  USING SODIUM BICARBONATE, I NEUTRALIZED THE ACID THEN USED SPEEDY-DRY TO SOLIDIFY THAT WHICH THE SODIUM BICARBONATE COULD NOT SOLIDIFY.  WEARING PPE, I CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL ACCORDING TO UPS DMP PROCEDURES.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

AT APPROX 7:40 AM ON 11/1/94 DERRICK GETTIS FOUND THE LEAKING PACKAGE. HE DIDN'T TOUCH THE PKG. HE LEFT THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED ME (TIM INGRAM) IMMEDIATELY. THE TRAILER WAS #280863. I THEN NOTIFIED THE RESPONDERS (GARY ANDERSON AND TRACY PARKER). THEY RETURNED TO THE DECISION TREE, LOCATED THE PROPER RESPONSE SHEET THEN PROCEEDED IN CLEANING UP THE SPILL. WE FOUND THAT THE CAP WAS LOOSE ON THE BOTTLE OF DRAIN CLEANER ALLOWING IT TO LEAK.

HILL WAS MAKING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS IN NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD HE OBSERVED LIQUID ON TOP OF TANK CAR FPAX 931104, HIS INSPECTION REVEALED A FAILED 100 PSI, B.S.&.B. FRANGIBLE DISC. A NEW PSI, B.S.& B. DISC WAS PLACED IN SAFETY VENT LOCATED ON TOP OF MANWAY COVER, HAD BAFFLE TYPE REDUCED RUPTURE SYSTEM. CHEMTREC'S JOE MILLAZZO RECEIVED THE REPORT ON THIS INCIDENT. column168: ON 111794 AT APPROXIMATELY 11AM MTO PENNINGTON NOTIFIED REEDER THAT THE CARMEN HAD DISCOVERED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER NOTED THE CAR DRIPPING ABOUT 1 DROP EVERY 2 TO 3 SECONDS. SEAL "GRIBBLE STAMP" 233714 WAS REMOVED FROM THE TOP OPERATING HANDLE. THE VALVE WAS OPEN APPROXIMATELY 3/4 TURN. THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS ALSO TIGHTENED ABOUT 1 TURN. THE HOUSING WAS RESEALED WITH UP 483336. THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TURNED ABOUT 1 TURN TO GET IT COMPLETELY TIGHT. THESE ACTIONS STOPPED THE LEAK. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO CHEMTREC ON THEIR INCIDENT NUMBER 32257.

column168: ON 111794 AT APPROXIMATELY 9AM FRA INSPECTOR LOUIS RICHARDS OBSERVED THE ABOVE CAR WITH A LIQUID STAIN RUNNING FROM THE MANWAY COVER TO ABOUT HALF WAY DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. HE HAD THE TRAIN CREW STOP THEIR TRAIN AND SET OUT THE CAR FOR INSPECTION. THIS CAUSED A DELAY TO YARD OPERATIONS OF ABOUT 2 HOURS. REEDER ARRIVED AND NOTED THE STAIN APPEARED TO ORIGINATE FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE GASKET. SEAL S110011289 WAS REMOVED AND THE COVER OPENED. THE MANWAY COVER SEAL WAS SPLIT, LEAVING AN OPENING ABOUT 1/4" WIDE. REEDER FORMED A NEW GASKET FROM GORE TAX AND CLOSED THE MANWAY COVER. SEAL UP 483323 WAS APPLIED. THIS INCIDENT CARRIES CHEMTREC REPORT #32258.

column168: AT 0150 HRS ON 11-16-94 CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY WEST HUMPMASTER MERLE STILLWELL. HE ADVISED THAT, TANK CAR ACFX 73136 CONTAINING METHYL TERT BUTYL ETHER, LOCATED IN WEST RECEIVING TRACK 4 WAS LEAKING. ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER CAR TO CAPTURE PRODUCT WHICH WAS DRIPPING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 60 DROPS A MINUTE. INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS: THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT TIGHT. UPON TURNING VALVE CLOSED 1/2 TURN, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE PACKING GLAND NUT TO THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS FOUND LOOSE AND RELEASING VAPOR, NUT TIGHTENED 1 TURN. BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP LOOSE, TIGHTENED 1/8 TURN. UPON TIGHTENING OF ALL FITTINGS, CAR WAS SECURED. NOTIFICATION: 0255 HRS, 11-16-94, CHEM-TREC, JOE RAZALAN, #32230; 0300HRS, UPPR E.M.C. STEVE MCNAUGHTON; 1000HRS, NEBRASKA D.E.Q.

column168: AT 04:11 ON11/08/94, RAMP SUPERVISOR CHRIS PRICE REPORTED AN ODOR TOPSIDE OF AIRCRAFT 982AX PARKED AT GATE B31 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH,45177.  CHRIS ADVISED THE ODOR WAS EMITTING FROM A CONTAINER WHICH HAD JUST BEEN LOADED.  HAZMAT COORDINATOR, FRAN VANCE, AND P/T HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN, RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL, CHRIS PRICE ADVISED US THAT HE HAD CHECKED TH CONTAINER AND FOUND A LEAKING SHIPMENT OF PAINT.  WE REMOVED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT AND CONTAINER FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CHECKED, AND WE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A GREY PAINT TYPE LIQUID.  THIS LIQUID HAD LEAKED UPON MOST OF THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER.  DUE TO THE HOUR, I REQUESTED ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE FROM HAZMAT DISPATCH. P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS, MARK GRIFFITH AND DAVID JARRELL RESPONDED.  WE SEPARATED THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER.  THE FREIGHT THAT WAS NOT DAMAGED BY THE SPILL WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION.  THE FREIGHT THAT WAS DAMAGED WAS HELD TO BE DECONTAMINATED AND REPACKAGED.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN 2 1-GALLON METAL CONTAINERS OF "TCI-350-CP" GAS TANK SEALANT.  ATTACHED TO THE CLOSURES OF INNER METAL CONTAINER WAS A CLASS 3 LABEL.  BOTH INNER METAL CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THE METAL CONTAINERS WERE LOADED IN THE FIBREBOARD BOX ON THEIR SIDES,WITH THE CLOSURES FACING INWARD.  THERE WAS NO ORIENTATION INDICATED ON THE INNER OR OUTER CONTAINERS.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED AND TAGGED TO BE HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY AREA.  SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN ON HOLD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELS, PROPER CERTIFICATION ON THE OUTER BOX TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET HAS BEEN REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER.

ON 11/11/94 HAZMAT TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN, AND HAZMAT TECHNICIAN, CAROLYN CORDREY, RESPONDED TO A SPILL WITH AND ODOR AT THE HAZ SORT.  AFTER DONNING PPE, TECHNICIAN CAROLYN CORDREY BEGAN HER INVESTIGATION OF THE PACKAGE.  SHE DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE WAS DAMP, AND THE INNER CONTENTS WERE LEAKING.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THE INNER CONTENTS CONTAINED 4 PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  THE CLOSURES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  HOWEVER, THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 11/10/94 AT 02:29, BETTY COCHRAN, SORT SUPERVISOR, REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS LEAKING WITH AN ODOR.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX, THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE WET.  AFTER INVESTIGATING FURTHER, IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A GLASS JAR WITH SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES AND PACKED WITH PAPER CLIPS.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED ONE GLASS JAR.  THE CONTENTS OF THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED OUTSIDE THE PACKAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT IS A XYLENE SOLUTION. THIS SHIPMENT IS REGULATED BY THE DOT AND IS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMNET TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

THE DOCK WORKER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF FLUID ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM DURING UNLOADING.  WHEN THE DRUM WAS MOVED, BUBBLES WOULD APPEAR AROUND THE SCREW ON THE CLOSURE.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR THE MATERIAL TO BE TRANSFERED TO ANOTHER DRUM AND REMOVED THE DEFECTIVE ONE.

THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED AT 14 DOOR 211880 MEAN J AT 00:37.  I RESPONDED TO THE CALL WITH MY PPE. A PREPARED SPILL TUB, THE DECISION TREE, AND RESPONSE SHEET, AFTER CONSULTING THE DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET I MADE A PH TEST.  SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID.  I THEN RETURNED TO THE PSC WITH THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE DMP WAS STARTED AT 00:48 COMPLETED AT 01:36.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF UNDER THE HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO THE UST'S AT A CONVENIENCE STORE. HE HAD COMPLETED DELIVERING THE SUPER UNLEADED AND HAD CAPPED THE TANK WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS. OUR DRIVER THEN STARTED TO UNLOAD THE MID-GRADE GAS FOR THE STATION. WHILE THE MID GRADE WAS UNLOADING, HE WENT BACK TO THE SUPER TANK TO TAKE THE STICK READINGS. WHEN HE PULLED THE CAP OFF THE FILL PIPE THE GAS SHOT UP OUT OF IT AND SPLASHED INTO OUR DRIVER'S EYES. THE GAS RAN DOWN THE BLACKTOP AND ALONG THE EDGE OF THE PARKING LOT. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED AND HAD SAND BROUGHT IN TO COVER THE GAS UNTIL LUZON ENVIRONMENTAL CREWS COULD ARRIVE TO DO THE CLEANUP. OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO ARDEN HILL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY AFTER HAVING HIS EYES TREATED. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED REFERENCE #94-11390 TO THE INCIDENT: THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR REPORT NUMBER IS 270975. THE SPILL APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A VENTING SYSTEM MALFUNCTION.

CLEAN HARBORS CLEANED THE ENVIRONMENT AND OH MATERIALS TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT INTO CELX 3272.  BOE INSPECTOR A.W. RICHTER, AT CONRAILS'S REQUEST, OVER SAW THE TRANSFER OPERATION AND EXAMINED OF THE "A" SILL, AT SPACES WHERE THE JACKET MET THE SILL.  THE ORIGIN OF THE LEAK COULD NOT BE DETERMINED AS THE CAR WAS JACKETED. SHIPPER TO GET AN EXEMPTION TO MOVE CAR TO A SHOP.

AT 22:30 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 1ST, FRA HAZ/MAT INSPECTOR J. CONNELLY DISCOVERED GATX 45071, IN TRAIN COCS1, TO BE LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT OF THE TRAIN.  RESCAR WAS CONTRACTED TO REPAIR CAR.  THEY FOUND 15 INCHES OF THE MANWAY GASKET MISSING AND THE FRANGIBLE DISC IMPROPERLY APPLIED. THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORATION AT 17:30 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 2ND.

ON 11-13-94 AT 12:02 SORT LEAD LINDA WILSON REPORTED A BOX OF LEAKING FINGERNAIL POLISH INSIDE DOORC9, OF BUILDING C OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177. HAZ MAT COORD FRAN VANCE RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND ONE BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG LEAKING A RED LIQUID, BOX WAS OPEN AND SMALL BOTTLES OF FINGERNAIL POLISH WERE VISIBLE. THE BOX WAS RESEALED AND PLACED INSIDE A SECOND PLASTIC BAG AND PLACED INSIDE THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA. THERE WERE NO NAPKINS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ATTACHED OR ACCOMPANYING OUTSIDE PACKAGED MARKINGS WERE AS FOLLOWS, FRAGILE, ORIENTATION ARROWS AND DOT-E9275. CAUTION ON THE INDIVIDUAL NAIL POLISH BOTTLES: KEEP FROM HEAT OR FLAME. CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE SCREW TYPE CLOSURES ON THE NAIL POLISH BOTTLES. APPROX. 88.8ML LEAKED. TOTAL AMOUNT INCLUDED IN THIS BOX, 3, 996 ML (APPROX. 1 GALLON).

AT 07:35 A CALL ABOUT A LIQUID DAMAGE ON BOXLINE 4 WAS MADE TO THE DMP AREA BY JOE WEISS.  J. PARRINO RESPONDED TO THE CALL WITH THE SPILL CART. DECISION TREE RESPONSE WAS FOLLOWED FOR POISONOUS HARMFUL SUBSTANCES.  NO FREE LIQUID NO BOOTS NEEDED.  NO ODOR NO SCBA USED. M. OSCHOTORENA RESTRICTED THE AREA.  DAMAGE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN SPILL TRAY AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP AREA AND WAS PROCESSED THROUGH UPS DMP PROCEDURE.  NO INJURIES OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS DAMAGE.  INFORMATION ABOUT THIS DAMAGE FORWARDED TO SORT MANAGER FOR REVIEW.

column168: MOBIL DRIVER, L ROOD, FAILED TO PROPERLY ATTACH THE DELIVERY HOSE CONNECTION TO THE UST FILL PIPE CONNECTION.  THE CONNECTIONS WERE NOT PROPERLY SEATED IN THE DILL PIPE GROOVE.  WHEN THE TANKER VALVE WAS OPENED, THE CONNECTION LEAKED OUT CAUSING THE FILL BOX TO FILL UP AND OVER FLOW ONTO THE PAVEMENT AREA.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE TANKER VALVE AND SECURED TANKER.   THE STATION ATTENDANT SECURED THE AREA FROM THE PUBLIC, PROVIDED SPEEDY DRY TO CONTAIN THE SPILL, AND CALLED FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE STATE POLICE REQUESTED THE TANKER BE MOVED FORWARD FROM THE SPILL AREA. THE TANKER WAS ROLLED FORWARD WITHOUT STARTING ENGINE.  DRIVER CALLED SUPERVISOR, WHO CALLED IN A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR AND LSI TO MONITOR SITE. STATE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED IN AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  EMPLOYEE WAS COUNSELED ON THE PROPER WAY TO HOOK UP DELIVERY HOSE CONNECTION TO THE UST FILL PIPE AND CHECK FOR A PROPER FIT AND LOCK ON.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 19-5330, OUR EMPLOYEE CAME ACROSS THE CARTON ON PRO 123-455710.  THE EMPLOYEE NOTICED THAT THE CARTON HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE WATER STAINS ON IT.  THE EMPLOYEE HEARD BROKEN GLASS WHEN HE MOVED THE CARTON AND CALLED THE FREIGHT OPERATIONS MANAGER OVER.  THE OPS MGR CLEARED THE AREA, CALLED CHEMTREC, AND SPOKE TO LARRY DOLAY WHO ADVISED HIM THAT WHEN CHLOROFORM EVAPORATES, THERE IS NO LONGER A HAZARD.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND FAXED A COPY OF THE MSDS SHEET.  SAFETY SUPERVISOR, JACK HAEN, WAS CONTACTED THE NEXT DAY, ALONG WITH REPORTING THE INCIDENT TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #270444).  THE CARTON WAS ISOLATED AND HELD FOR 12 HOURS TO ASSURE IT WAS DRY AND THEN MOVED TO DESTINATION FOR DELIVERY.  THIS WAS DONE BASED ON THE INFORMATION PROVIDED FROM CHEMTREC.
LEAKING PACKAGE DISCOVERED ON GREEN BELT.  LOOSE LID/SEAL.  LEAK WAS ABSORBED BY CARTON.  REPACKED UNDAMAGED ITEMS AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. PROCESSED CARTON THROUGH UPS DMP PROGRAM.
PACKAGE IN COMPLIANCE.  IT IS NOW AWAITING DISPOSAL IN THE DMP SYSTEM.

AFTER REVIEWING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET I RESPONDED TO 80 DOOR WEARING GOGGLES GLOVES APRON AND BOOTS.  I PLACED THE LEAKER IN A SPILL TUB WITH SPEEDY DRY AND SOLUSORB. column168: S/A BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM MTO DOUG BREWER THAT TANKCAR GATX-49195 WAS FOUND BY THE CREW TO BE LEAKING. THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN WEST SACRAMENTO AT 15TH STREET. THE LEAK THEN STOPPED.  NEW ENERGY COMPANY OF INDIAN WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THE CAR PRESSURE WAS 85 PSI.  FARMLAND REPRESENTATIVE JACK CURRY STATED THAT IT SOUNDED LIKE A BO "O" RING AND ARRANGED FOR A REPAIR TEAM.  NO TEAMS WERE AVAILABLE ACCT FOG.  THEY FOUND A RUBBER "O" RING, PARTIALLY MELTED AND BRITTLE.  THIS WAS CHIPPED OUT AND A NEOPRENE "O" RING APPLIED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT 1500 HRS., 11-26-94.

column168: UPRR MMM JOE PIAZZA REPORTED A STRONG ODOR IN TRACK 311, ON THE EAST END. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED AND LOCATED TANK CAR NATX 50771 AT THE WEST END OF TRACK 311.  IT HAD A SIMILAR ODOR AND PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR.  THE PLACARDS WERE SO FADED AS TO BE ILLEGIBLE AND THE WAYBILL LISTED IT AS A RESIDUE EMPTY.  THE LIQUID/AIR LINE HOUSING WAS SEALED, BUT THE 8 MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE ALL DOWN.  MS. ROQUET OPENED THE MANWAY TO CHECK THE GASKET AND OBSERVED THAT THE CAR WAS FULL.  SHE SECURED THE MANWAY AND HAD THE PLACARDS REPLACED.  THE EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE WAYBILL WAS CHEMTREC, BUT TOM FLORES, REPORT #32345, STATED THAT THE SHIPPER WAS NOT LISTED WITH THEM.  HE CONTACTED PROCTER & GAMBLE REPRESENTATIVE PHIL JOHNSON, 713-947-1706.  MR. JOHNSON SUGGESTED THAT THE CAR MAY HAVE BEEN RELEASED IN ERROR BY HURRICANE IRON STEEL AND REQUESTED THAT IT BE RETURNED TO THEIR FACILITY FOR OFFLOADING.  THIS REQUEST WAS FAXED TO CUSTOMER SERVICE, 1-800-877-7610.  THE CAR WAS BILLED OUT AS A LOAD UNDER MP WB 11 23 744083.

REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS ADVISED AT 0840 HOURS BY MIKE ERWIN MANAGER QUALITY THAT A CAR OF NITRATES WAS ON FIRE AT THE A-1 RIP TRACK. UPON ARRIVAL AT 0900 HOURS MR. STINE CONTACTED KANSAS CITY KANSAS FIRE DISTRICT CHIEF TONY KNOVAK AND ASSISTANT CHIEF ROBERT HORN AT THE COMMAND POST WHICH WAS EAST OF THE BURNING CAR 1/4TH MILE. WEATHER AT THIS TIME WAS AN OVERCAST SKY, WIND SSE 9-14 MPH TEMP 45. FIRE OFFICERS ADVISED THEY HAD INSTITUTED A VOLUNTARY EVACUATION IN AN AREA FROM CHEYENNE AVENUE TO CENTRAL AVENUE AND I-70. (THIS BRIDGE PASSES OVER THE RAIL YARD JUST WEST OF THE FIRE LOCATION. NEWS PRINT INDICATED 3000 PERSONS EVACUATED INCLUDING SIX SCHOOLS. PUMPER 3 HAD BEEN THE FIRST ARRIVING UNIT AT 0812 HOURS AND ORDERED A GENERAL ALARM INCLUDING HAZ/MAT. FURTHER KCK FIRE HAD REQUESTED MUTUAL AID FROM KC, MO FIRE AND OVERLAND PARK KANSAS FIRE. KC MO WAS DISPATCHED AT 0919 HOURS AND OVERLAND PARK AT 0929 HOURS. THESE DEPARTMENTS WERE USED FOR AIR MONITORING OF THE AREA WITH NO ABNORMAL READINGS DETECTED. AT 0915 HOURS CHIEF HORN AND MR. STINE ENTERED THE HOT ZONE AND CHECKED CAR AND FIRE FINDING THE MATERIAL HAD FALLEN THROUGH THE BURNT OUT FLOOR OF THE CAR AND WAS MELTING WITH THE LIQUID FLOWING INTO A SEWER GRATE JUST WEST OF THE BURNING CAR. THE SEWER GRATE HAD BLOWN OFF WHEN THE MOLTEN MATERIAL HIT THE WATER IN THE 18" SEWER PIPE. ALSO A GRATE WAS OFF 50 FEET TOWARD THE SOUTHWEST, HOWEVER THE MATERIAL WAS BECOMING SOLIDIFIED. IT WAS DECIDED TO LET THE CAR BURN 30 MINUTES AND GET TANKERS OF WATER AS THERE IS NO HYDRANTS LOCATED FOR USE. OVERLAND PARK AND EDWARDVILLE, KANSAS FIRE DEPARTMENTS SUPPLIED THE WATER TANKERS TO SUPPRESS THE FIRE. DIRECTOR L.R.TIERNEY AND MR. STINE OPENED THE PLUG DOOR ON THE SOUTH SIDE AND DIRECTED FIRE CREWS EXTINGUISHED THE SLIGHT AMOUNT OF FIRE INSIDE THE CAR WITH A VERY MINIMAL AMOUNT OF WATER BEING USED. PRIOR TO THIS THE DRAIN HAD BEEN COVERED WITH PLASTIC AND AB3 ROCK SO ANY POSSIBILITY OF WATER ENTERING THE SEWER WAS ELIMINATED. HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, INC., A LOCAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, HAD BEEN ALERTED AT 1010 HOURS AND STARTED CLEANUP OF THE MATERIAL IMMEDIATELY, PLACING IT INTO NINE 20 CUBIC YARD ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS WHICH ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSAL. CLEANING OF THE SEWER AND DISPOSAL IS BEING HANDLED BY MARK SCHAFER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS. LAW DEPARTMENT AND CLAIM DEPARTMENT WERE ON SITE AND HANDLED ANY REPORTED INJURIES.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A PLASTIC DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. THE DRUM WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER LABELS AND MARKINGS. column168: AT 1619 HRS. CENTRAL ON 11/19/94, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM DARRYLL BANKS AT OUR COLUMBUS, OHIO RAMP HE INDICATED HE HAD OPENED THE BACK DOORS ON A TRACTOR TRAILER AND DISCOVERED A BOX LISTED AS ARTICLES PRESSURIZED, PNEUMATIC THAT WAS LEAKING AN UNDETERMINED LIQUID. DARRYL CALLED THE 24 HOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE # AT 800-528-8993. DARRYLL WAS TOLD BY THE PERSON THAT ANSWERED THE PHONE THAT THEY COULD NOT FAX AN MSDS UNTIL MONDAY. UPON HEARING THIS I CALLED 800-528-8993, THERE WAS NO ANSWER. I CALLED THREE TIMES, JUST TO MAKE SURE I DIALED CORRECTLY. I HAD, SINCE THE BUSINESS CLOSES AT 1630 CENTRAL, NO ONE IS AVAILABLE TO ANSWER THE PHONE. I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE FAA GREAT LAKES DUTY OFFICER. KATHY FROM FAA CASFO-CLEVELAND CALLED ME BACK AND I WAS ADVISED. I SPOKE TO DIANE COUTURIER AND SHE CONFIRMED THAT THE 24 HR # IS NO GOOD AFTER 1630 CENTRAL AS SHE IS THE SHIPPER.

column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: AS THE BOX WAS BEING SORTED, FROST ON THE BOX WAS NOTICED. THE BOX WAS OPENED AND DRY ICE WAS IN THE BOX. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELING TO INDICATED THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED DANGEROUS GOODS. SINCE THE FAA IS ABOUT 4 HRS AWAY BY CAR, I TOOK PICTURES OF THE BOX AND IT'S CONTENTS. I ALSO NOTIFIED THE FAA AND THE SHIPPER. IN MY DISCUSSION WITH DENISE SLATER, SHE SAID SHE ASKED FEDEX (OUR CALL CENTER) FOR A DRY ICE LABEL. THE COURIER DID NOT HAVE ONE AND REFUSED THE FREIGHT. THE SHIPPER BOOKED ANOTHER PICK UP WITH THE CALL CENTER AND WE SENT ANOTHER COURIER. THE BOX WAS PICKED UP. BUT NO MENTION OF DRY ICE WAS MADE. DENISE THEN TOLD ME THAT SHE TOUGHT THAT IF THE DRY ICE WAS UNDER 2POUNDS THAT SHE DIDN'T HAVE TO DECLARE IT. I ADVISED HER OTHERWISE.

column168: RAILROAD TANK CAR LTCX 1802 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN DERAMUS YARD, SHREVEPORT, LOUISIANA ON 11/18/94 AT 2215 HRS.  THE RESPONSIBLE KCS OFFICIALS WERE NOTIFIED AT 2220 HRS ON 11/18/94.  THE CAR WAS THEN ISOLATED.  CHEMTREC (TRACY) WAS NOTIFIED AT 2220 HRS, REPORT #32264. CHEMTREC THEN NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE NOTIFIED KCS THAT A PERSON WAS ENROUTE TO MAKE REPAIRS AT 0330 HRS ON 11/19/94.  THE CAR WAS REPAIRED (VALVE TIGHTENED) AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO SERVICE AT 0445 HRS ON 11/19.  **PLEASE NOTE THAT THE RELEASE AT DERAMUS YARD WAS MINIMAL, AND THIS CONSIDERED AS A NON-EMERGENCY SITUATION. DISCUSSION WITH THE SHIPPER INDICATED THAT THE WEIGHT LOSS, AS CLAIMED BY THEIR SHIPPER, WAS PORTAL TO PORTAL WEIGHT LOSS.  THE SHIPPER INDICATED THAT THE CAR WAS MORE THAN LIKELY LEAKING IN TRANSIT.
